================================================================================
PROBLEM: Happy Number (Hinglish Notes)
================================================================================

### 💡 Core Logic (Approach)
1. Kisi bhi number ke digits ke squares ka sum baar-baar nikalte jana hai.
2. Agar ye process karte-karte number '1' ban jata hai, to wo Happy Number hai 
   (Return true).
3. Agar number '1' nahi banta, to wo ek endless loop (cycle) me phas jayega. 
   Is cycle ko pakadne ke liye hum HashSet ka use karte hain.
4. Loop ke andar check karo:
   - Agar current number pehle se HashSet me hai, iska matlab loop start ho gaya hai 
     aur ye kabhi '1' nahi banega. Turant return false kar do.
   - Agar nahi hai, to use set me add karo aur number ko uske "sum of squares" 
     se replace kar do.

---

### 🔍 Dry Run / Testcase
Input Number: n = 19
HashSet: {} (Initial)

- Iteration 1: n = 19 (Not 1, Not in Set)
  -> Set me dala: {19}
  -> Sum of Squares: 1^2 + 9^2 = 1 + 81 = 82
  -> New n = 82

- Iteration 2: n = 82 (Not 1, Not in Set)
  -> Set me dala: {19, 82}
  -> Sum of Squares: 8^2 + 2^2 = 64 + 4 = 68
  -> New n = 68

- Iteration 3: n = 68 (Not 1, Not in Set)
  -> Set me dala: {19, 82, 68}
  -> Sum of Squares: 6^2 + 8^2 = 36 + 64 = 100
  -> New n = 100

- Iteration 4: n = 100 (Not 1, Not in Set)
  -> Set me dala: {19, 82, 68, 100}
  -> Sum of Squares: 1^2 + 0^2 + 0^2 = 1
  -> New n = 1

- Loop Ends! Kyuki n == 1 ho gaya hai.
👉 Result: Return true

---

### ⏱️ Complexity
- Time Complexity: O(log N) -> Digits ke square ka sum bohot tezi se chhota hota hai.
- Space Complexity: O(log N) -> Unique sums ko store karne ke liye HashSet ka space.
